    {
      "id": "singapore-entrepot",
      "name": "The Singapore entrepôt (the free port, 1819–1850)",
      "evidence": "counted",
      "basis": "Raffles founded the free port 6 Feb 1819; it became the hinge of the eastern-archipelago trade where three rhythms met — year-round European square-rig on the Calcutta↔Singapore↔Canton arterial (opium out, tea/goods home), Amoy China junks on the NE monsoon (arrive Jan–Mar, first Amoy junk 19 Feb 1821), and Bugis prahus arriving Sept–Oct. The counted backbone is Wong Lin Ken's Master-Attendant returns — square-rig entries 139 (1822) → 517 (1834) → ~1028 (1854); native craft 2310 (1854); trade value $0.4M (1819) → $17.8M (1830) → $14.2M (1835 dip) → $25.2M (1850). It rests on ONE compiler (counted/medium), and the decade voyage RANGES here are reconstructed BETWEEN the three counted vessel-count years and stated as bounds — no fabricated annual precision. Foreign-going basis (R1): square-rig + long-haul junks + the larger Bugis prahus; the mass of tiny intra-archipelago native craft sits below the threshold and is excluded (a declared boundary, not a silent zero). The ~5,000–7,000 Chinese labourers/yr from ~1830 ride the Amoy-junk lane under the sober pattern (asserted-with-bounds), not a separate system.",
      "era": {
        "from": 1819,
        "to": 1850
      },
      "cargo": ["opium", "tea", "textiles", "specie", "spices", "pepper", "trade-goods"],
      "shipTypes": ["east-indiaman", "merchantman", "junk", "dhow"],
